1
00:00:00,789 --> 00:00:04,740
The average true range is a great tool, when
it comes to adapting to the ever-changing

2
00:00:04,740 --> 00:00:09,210
market environment, being a useful indicator
in measuring volatility.

3
00:00:09,210 --> 00:00:13,560
The average true range measures the price
range of an asset – the higher the volatility

4
00:00:13,560 --> 00:00:14,929
the higher the ATR.

5
00:00:14,929 --> 00:00:18,820
The average true range is one of the most
useful indicators because it helps the trader

6
00:00:18,820 --> 00:00:23,550
deciding on where will set a stop loss or
profit target, or if he even should open a

7
00:00:23,550 --> 00:00:24,950
trade in the first place.

8
00:00:24,950 --> 00:00:30,360
The ATR is measured as the greatest of any
of the following 3 metrics:

9
00:00:30,360 --> 00:00:33,090
• the value of the current high minus the
low;

10
00:00:33,090 --> 00:00:36,520
• the distance of the current high minus
the previous close;

11
00:00:36,520 --> 00:00:41,090
• the distance of the current low minus
the previous close

12
00:00:41,090 --> 00:00:45,240
Despite the fact the Average True Range is
not so common among traders, this indicator

13
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:48,350
can assist them in entering and exiting trades.

14
00:00:48,350 --> 00:00:53,620
The ATR indicator moves up and down as price
movements become larger or smaller.

15
00:00:53,620 --> 00:00:57,440
A new ATR reading is calculated as each time
period passes.

16
00:00:57,440 --> 00:01:02,170
On a one-minute chart, a new ATR reading is
calculated every minute.

17
00:01:02,170 --> 00:01:05,710
On a daily chart, a new ATR is calculated
every day.

18
00:01:05,710 --> 00:01:10,960
All these readings are plotted to form a continuous
line, so traders can see how volatility has

19
00:01:10,960 --> 00:01:12,820
changed over time.

20
00:01:12,820 --> 00:01:18,350
An asset’s range is the difference between
the highest price and lowest price on a given

21
00:01:18,350 --> 00:01:19,350
day.

22
00:01:19,350 --> 00:01:23,780
The Average True Range reveals information
about how volatile the asset actually is.

23
00:01:23,780 --> 00:01:29,460
High ranges reveal high volatility while small
ranges suggest low volatility.

24
00:01:29,460 --> 00:01:32,640
The average true range (ATR) is basically
an exponential moving average of the true

25
00:01:32,640 --> 00:01:33,940
range.

26
00:01:33,940 --> 00:01:37,780
Most common settings of this indicator are
the 14-day ATR.

27
00:01:37,780 --> 00:01:42,640
Depending on their trading objectives or the
time frames, traders can use shorter or longer

28
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:45,630
inputs of the ATR.

29
00:01:45,630 --> 00:01:49,909
longer ATR will be slower and will generate
fewer trading signals

30
00:01:49,909 --> 00:01:54,970
shorter ATR will generate a higher number
of trading signals and will increase trading

31
00:01:54,970 --> 00:01:57,299
activity
For example:

32
00:01:57,299 --> 00:02:02,170
An average true range of only 5 periods would
not offer a large enough sample to generate

33
00:02:02,170 --> 00:02:05,630
an accurate indication of the true range of
the security

34
00:02:05,630 --> 00:02:09,979
An average true range of 50 periods would
generate a more smooth average true range

35
00:02:09,979 --> 00:02:14,340
on the chart, with fewer and possibly high-quality
signals.

36
00:02:14,340 --> 00:02:19,790
Let’s assume that you are using a swing
trading strategy and you’re using an ATR

37
00:02:19,790 --> 00:02:21,680
with a 50-period input.

38
00:02:21,680 --> 00:02:26,029
You should keep in mind that if you’re trading
on the daily chart, the ATR indicator will

39
00:02:26,029 --> 00:02:30,120
indicate the average volatility over the past
50 days.

40
00:02:30,120 --> 00:02:35,450
However, if you’re trading on the H4 chart,
the ATR indicator will display the average

41
00:02:35,450 --> 00:02:39,129
volatility over the past 50 H4 candles.

42
00:02:39,129 --> 00:02:46,360
So ATR’s value differs from time frame to
time frame, is not a unique value.

43
00:02:46,360 --> 00:02:52,079
How To Read Average True Range Indicator
First, ATR represents a range indicator for

44
00:02:52,079 --> 00:02:56,150
filtering out trades
If you prefer volatile markets or if your

45
00:02:56,150 --> 00:03:01,430
trading strategy is based on huge market moves,
then ATR can filter out markets that are low

46
00:03:01,430 --> 00:03:03,230
in volatility.

47
00:03:03,230 --> 00:03:07,269
Even if you prefer calm, quiet markets the
average true range indicator will help you

48
00:03:07,269 --> 00:03:11,329
to filter out those periods of times that
you would prefer to avoid.

49
00:03:11,329 --> 00:03:15,829
It is important to remember that the ATR does
not measure the market direction.

50
00:03:15,829 --> 00:03:20,909
By tracking the average true range, a trader
cannot identify the prevailing trend on the

51
00:03:20,909 --> 00:03:21,909
market.

52
00:03:21,909 --> 00:03:26,480
The ATR only tracks the magnitude of range,
so it has limited use for generating accurate

53
00:03:26,480 --> 00:03:27,480
trading signals.

54
00:03:27,480 --> 00:03:32,650
It’s a useful indicator only for giving
an idea about how much the price may move

55
00:03:32,650 --> 00:03:35,810
in a defined time frame.

56
00:03:35,810 --> 00:03:39,040
Assume a stock moves $1 a day, on average.

57
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:43,879
There is no significant news out, but price
has already moved let’s say 30% more than

58
00:03:43,879 --> 00:03:47,980
the average, and now you're getting a buy
signal from a strategy.

59
00:03:47,980 --> 00:03:52,430
The buy signal may be valid but, since the
price has already moved significantly more

60
00:03:52,430 --> 00:03:56,959
than average, betting that the price will
continue to go up and expand the range even

61
00:03:56,959 --> 00:03:59,489
further may not be a prudent decision.

62
00:03:59,489 --> 00:04:01,919
The trade goes against the odds.

63
00:04:01,919 --> 00:04:06,549
Since the price is already up substantially
and has moved more than the average, the price

64
00:04:06,549 --> 00:04:11,159
is more likely to fall and stay within the
price range already established.

65
00:04:11,159 --> 00:04:16,459
While buying once the price is near the top
of the daily range isn't prudent, shorting

66
00:04:16,459 --> 00:04:20,610
is probably a good option, assuming a valid
sell signal occurs.

67
00:04:20,610 --> 00:04:27,110
Now, very important: Entries and exits should
not be based on the ATR alone.

68
00:04:27,110 --> 00:04:32,890
The ATR is a tool that should be used in conjunction
with a strategy to help filtering trades.

69
00:04:32,890 --> 00:04:37,190
For example, in the previous situation, you
shouldn't sell simply because the price has

70
00:04:37,190 --> 00:04:40,930
moved up and the daily range is larger than
usual.

71
00:04:40,930 --> 00:04:45,630
You short only if a valid sell signal occurs,
based on your particular strategy.

72
00:04:45,630 --> 00:04:51,620
Second, the ATR formula will assist you in
setting profit targets

73
00:04:51,620 --> 00:04:56,680
Knowing the average range is extremely useful
since it allows the trader to estimate how

74
00:04:56,680 --> 00:04:59,630
much profit potential there is in the market.

75
00:04:59,630 --> 00:05:04,880
For example, there is no point looking for
200 pips of profit from a trade in a currency

76
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:11,260
pair, if the average true range for that market
over the last 14 days is only 60 points.

77
00:05:11,260 --> 00:05:17,130
A simpler solution is to halve the 14-day
ATR of the instrument and use this figure

78
00:05:17,130 --> 00:05:18,730
as your profit target.

79
00:05:18,730 --> 00:05:24,400
Thus, after entering a trade in, you could
set yourself a profit target of around 30

80
00:05:24,400 --> 00:05:25,840
points.

81
00:05:25,840 --> 00:05:27,320
How To Trade With Average True Range

82
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:33,670
ATR Indicator is useful to identify low levels
of volatility

83
00:05:33,670 --> 00:05:37,250
Average True Range doesn’t tell the trader
anything about market direction.

84
00:05:37,250 --> 00:05:39,670
Don’t get confused about its direction.

85
00:05:39,670 --> 00:05:43,470
If the Average True Range is going up on the
chart, that doesn’t mean that the trend

86
00:05:43,470 --> 00:05:44,470
is up.

87
00:05:44,470 --> 00:05:49,630
A viable strategy would be to search for low
volatility levels, in order to find a trade

88
00:05:49,630 --> 00:05:53,000
in the direction of the main trend.

89
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:57,930
The first thing we need to do is to identify
where the low volatility actually is.

90
00:05:57,930 --> 00:06:02,690
Keep in mind that the low volatility itself
is not enough for a new trend.

91
00:06:02,690 --> 00:06:07,430
This translates into the fact that the current
trend has run out of steam, it doesn’t tell

92
00:06:07,430 --> 00:06:08,820
us that a new trend has begun.

93
00:06:08,820 --> 00:06:13,700
So, we must use the Average True Range in
conjunction with other oscillators or price

94
00:06:13,700 --> 00:06:14,790
action.

95
00:06:14,790 --> 00:06:19,730
For example, in this example we identified
low levels of volatility, but we cannot enter

96
00:06:19,730 --> 00:06:20,850
the market blindly.

97
00:06:20,850 --> 00:06:26,150
A smarter approach would be to wait for the
average true range to exit from that level

98
00:06:26,150 --> 00:06:31,150
and confirm the volatility increase with a
trend line breakout on the chart, or a rising

99
00:06:31,150 --> 00:06:38,520
Stochastic for example, or a divergence on
the RSI or CCI, depending on your strategy.

100
00:06:38,520 --> 00:06:41,930
Second strategy involves using ATR as a trailing
stop loss

101
00:06:41,930 --> 00:06:48,490
A trailing stop loss is a way to exit a trade
if the asset price moves against you but also

102
00:06:48,490 --> 00:06:53,020
enables you to move the exit point if the
price is moving in your favor.

103
00:06:53,020 --> 00:06:57,310
Many day traders use the ATR to figure out
where to put their trailing stop loss.

104
00:06:57,310 --> 00:07:02,340
Here’s how it works: at the time of a trade,
look at the current ATR reading.

105
00:07:02,340 --> 00:07:07,960
A rule of thumb is to multiply the ATR by
two to determine a reasonable stop loss point.

106
00:07:07,960 --> 00:07:13,730
So if you're buying a stock, you might place
a stop loss at a level twice the ATR below

107
00:07:13,730 --> 00:07:14,880
the entry price.

108
00:07:14,880 --> 00:07:19,540
If you're shorting a stock, you would place
a stop loss at a level twice the ATR above

109
00:07:19,540 --> 00:07:21,320
the entry price.

110
00:07:21,320 --> 00:07:25,910
If you're long and the price moves favorably,
continue to move the stop loss to twice the

111
00:07:25,910 --> 00:07:27,590
ATR below the price.

112
00:07:27,590 --> 00:07:31,620
In this scenario, the stop loss only moves
up, not down.

113
00:07:31,620 --> 00:07:37,680
Once it is moved up, it stays there until
it can be moved up again or the trade is closed

114
00:07:37,680 --> 00:07:42,220
as a result of the price dropping to hit the
trailing stop loss level.

115
00:07:42,220 --> 00:07:47,260
The same process works for short trades, only
in that case, the stop loss only moves down.

116
00:07:47,260 --> 00:07:54,240
For example, say you take a long trade at
$10 and the ATR is $0.10.

117
00:07:54,240 --> 00:08:00,419
You would place a stop loss at $9.80 (the
10 cents ATR multiplied by 2).

118
00:08:00,419 --> 00:08:05,250
The price rises to $10.20, and the ATR remains
at $0.10.

119
00:08:05,250 --> 00:08:08,260
The trailing stop loss is now moved up to
$10.

120
00:08:08,260 --> 00:08:16,169
When the price moves up to $10.50, the stop
loss moves up to $10.30, locking in at least

121
00:08:16,169 --> 00:08:18,640
a 30 cent profit on the trade.

122
00:08:18,640 --> 00:08:22,390
This would continue until the price falls
to hit the stop-loss point.

123
00:08:22,390 --> 00:08:25,680
Now, here’s an interesting indicator.

124
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:30,000
In order to make it easier to visually see
where those stops would be, you could use

125
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:31,850
the ATR bands.

126
00:08:31,850 --> 00:08:36,620
This indicator will show an upper and lower
band around the price, showing where you can

127
00:08:36,620 --> 00:08:40,329
put your stops (or trail them in open positions).

128
00:08:40,329 --> 00:08:45,209
You can use ATR bands in a number of ways:
• it’s an easy visual way to see where

129
00:08:45,209 --> 00:08:49,120
you can place your stop loss
• you can use a multiple of ATR as your

130
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:52,520
target
• you can trail your stops alongside the

131
00:08:52,520 --> 00:08:53,520
ATR bands

132
00:08:53,520 --> 00:08:59,809
ATR bands indicator has only 2 variables:
the period and the multiplier.

133
00:08:59,809 --> 00:09:06,899
By default, ATR period is set to 24 with the
rationale that one day has 24 hours so that

134
00:09:06,899 --> 00:09:10,079
way, we’re getting the average price movement
for the past day.

135
00:09:10,079 --> 00:09:14,921
However, if you’re day trading, it could
be useful to have a shorter ATR period, for

136
00:09:14,921 --> 00:09:19,140
example if you want to make recent price volatility
more relevant.

137
00:09:19,140 --> 00:09:22,839
ATR multiplier also depends on your trading
style.

138
00:09:22,839 --> 00:09:28,970
Let’s say your current ATR value is 20 pips
and you use a multiplier of 2, then the bands

139
00:09:28,970 --> 00:09:31,139
will be 40 pips on each side.

140
00:09:31,139 --> 00:09:36,240
If you use a multiplier of 3, the bands will
be 60 pips on each side.

141
00:09:36,240 --> 00:09:40,240
There is no universal rule for setting stops
according to the ATR.

142
00:09:40,240 --> 00:09:45,639
It depends on each trader’s individual risk
tolerance while also allowing the trade “breathing

143
00:09:45,639 --> 00:09:47,319
room” to develop.

144
00:09:47,319 --> 00:09:52,959
So backtest and choose the settings that are
in line with your strategy.

145
00:09:52,959 --> 00:09:57,720
As you probably know, one of the most important
aspects of trading and investing is having

146
00:09:57,720 --> 00:10:00,439
a disciplined risk management process.

147
00:10:00,439 --> 00:10:05,250
Because the ATR does not measure direction
and simply considers the magnitude of range,

148
00:10:05,250 --> 00:10:08,910
it has limited utility as a means for generating
trading signals.

149
00:10:08,910 --> 00:10:14,860
But it is a useful tool for providing an idea
about how much a market may move and will

150
00:10:14,860 --> 00:10:20,660
help you to apply a proper position size and
a proper stop placement.

151
